SIMPLE: marry
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Marry
<hw>Mar"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Married</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Marrying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>marien</ets>, F.
<ets>marier</ets>, L. <ets>maritare</ets>, fr. <ets>maritus</ets>
husband, fr. <ets>mas</ets>, <ets>maris</ets>, a male. See
<er>Male</er>, and cf. <er>Maritral</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
unite in wedlock or matrimony; to perform the ceremony of joining, as a
man and a woman, for life; to constitute (a man and a woman) husband and
wife according to the laws or customs of the place.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tell him that he shall <qex>marry</qex> the couple himself.</q>
<rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To join according to law, (a man) to a woman as his
wife, or (a woman) to a man as her husband. See the Note to def.
4.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A woman who had been <qex>married</qex> to her twenty-fifth
husband, and being now a widow, was prohibited to marry.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To dispose of in wedlock; to give away as
wife.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Maecenas took the liberty to tell him [Augustus] that he must
either <qex>marry</qex> his daughter [Julia] to Agrippa, or take away
his life.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To take for husband or wife. See the Note
below.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ We say, a man is <xex>married to</xex> or
<xex>marries</xex> a woman; or, a woman is <xex>married to</xex> or
<xex>marries</xex> a man. Both of these uses are equally well
authorized; but <xex>given in marriage</xex> is said only of the
woman.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They got him [the Duke of Monmouth] . . . to declare in writing,
that the last king [Charles II.] told him he was never
<qex>married</qex> to his mother.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Lloyd.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Figuratively, to unite in the closest and most
endearing relation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Turn, O backsliding children, saith the Lord; for I am
<qex>married</qex> unto you.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. iii. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To marry ropes</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>To place two ropes along side of each other so that they may be
grasped and hauled on at the same time</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To join
two ropes end to end so that both will pass through a block.</cd>
<rj><au>Ham. Nav. Encyc.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Marry
<hw>Mar"ry</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To enter into the conjugal or
connubial state; to take a husband or a wife.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will, therefore, that the younger women <qex>marry</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>1 Tim. v. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marrying man</b></col>, <cd>a man disposed to marry.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Marry
<hw>Mar"ry</hw>, <pos>interj.</pos> <def>Indeed! in truth! -- a term of
asseveration said to have been derived from the practice of swearing by
the Virgin Mary.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mars</ent>⟦br⟧
